

<div class="container">
    <div class="jumbotron">
        <h1>Anchors in Regular Expressions</h1>
        <p>Anchors in regular expressions allow you to match patterns that are anchored to specific positions in the text. They specify the position of the match within the input string.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2>Commonly Used Anchors</h2>
            <p>Here are some commonly used anchors in regular expressions:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>^</code> matches the start of a line or string.</li>
                <li><code>$</code> matches the end of a line or string.</li>
                <li><code>\b</code> matches a word boundary.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2>Usage</h2>
            <p>Anchors are useful when you want to match patterns only at specific positions within the input text. They help you ensure that a pattern occurs at the beginning, end, or boundaries of words.</p>
            <p>For example, <code>^h</code> matches a line or string that starts with "h", and <code>\btest\b</code> matches the word "test" as a whole word.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-12">
            <h2>Example: Matching the Start of a Line</h2>
            <p>This regular expression will match lines that start with "h":</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>^h</code> matches "hello", "hi", etc.</li>
                <li><code>^h</code> does not match "ahoy", "hey", etc.</li>
            </ul>
            <h2>Example: Matching the End of a Line</h2>
            <p>This regular expression will match lines that end with "!" at the end:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>!$</code> matches "Wow!", "Awesome!", etc.</li>
                <li><code>!$</code> does not match "Hello", "Hi!", etc.</li>
            </ul>
            <h2>Example: Matching Whole Words</h2>
            <p>This regular expression will match the word "regex" as a whole word:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><code>\bregex\b</code> matches "regex" but not "regex101", "regular", etc.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>